%I A393599 #28 Mar 02 2026 22:12:10
%S A393599 92,152,272,460,566,1540,2612,4516,8300,14504,25268,43016,77292,
%T A393599 134308,242412
%N A393599 Maximum width of a simple imperfect squared rectangle (SISR) of order n.
%C A393599 A squared rectangle is "simple" if it contains no smaller squared rectangle, and "imperfect" if at least two of its component squares share the same size. The width is defined as the maximum dimension of the bounding rectangle.
%C A393599 The maximum widths for a given order n were established through rigorous computational sweeps of planar graph embeddings mapped to electrical networks. After candidate square sizes are generated by solving for Kirchhoff's Current and Voltage laws.
%C A393599 The sequence relies on extracting absolute Cartesian coordinates directly from the graph topology: vertical boundaries are derived from primary graph node potentials via Kirchhoff's Voltage Law, while horizontal boundaries are derived from the node potentials of the dual graph. This method accurately resolves compound horizontal segments and guarantees that the recorded maximum widths belong to geometrically proven packings.
%D A393599 R. L. Brooks, C. A. B. Smith, A. H. Stone, and W. T. Tutte, The dissection of rectangles into squares, Duke Math. J. 7(1): 312-340 (1940).
%H A393599 Stuart E Anderson, <a href="https://www.squaring.net/sq/sr/sisr/sisr.html">Simple Imperfect Squared Rectangles, orders 9 to 24</a>.
%F A393599 Empirical logarithmic regression indicates asymptotic growth scaling at a factor of approximately 1.77 per order: W = exp(0.5688*n - 2.4002).
%e A393599 a(12) = 92:
%e A393599   *---------------*---------------*-------------*
%e A393599   |               |               |             |
%e A393599   |               |               |             |
%e A393599   |               |               |             |
%e A393599   |      31       |               |      28     |
%e A393599   |               |       33      |             |
%e A393599   |               |               |             |
%e A393599   |               |               |_____________|
%e A393599   *---------------+               |      |      |
%e A393599   |              |2_______________|  13  |  15  |
%e A393599   |              |            | 8 |      |      |
%e A393599   |              |            *----------|______|
%e A393599   |      29      |    27      |         2       |
%e A393599   |              |            |   19    |   17  |
%e A393599   |              |            |         |       |
%e A393599   |______________|____________|_________|_______|.
%e A393599 This establishes that the absolute maximum width of any simple imperfect squared rectangle dissected into exactly 12 squares is 92.
%Y A393599 Cf. A002881, A220165, A393598.
%K A393599 nonn,hard,more,new
%O A393599 12,1
